But I do not see that the sense is here interrupted. By nec vanos horret strepitus, the Poet means that a good eolt is not apt to start at the rustling of every leaf, at every little noise, that portends no danger. But by tum si qua sonum, &c- he means that the colt shews his mettle by exulting ata military noise, at which he erects his ears, bounds, paws, and is scarce able to contain himself. It not only is unnecessary, but would even be dull poetry, to give a regular, or.. derly description osa horse from head to tall.
